article.description:
Shawn Marion had 20 points and 12 rebounds as
the Phoenix Suns built a 22-point lead in the third quarter and
held on for an 87-76 victory over the Los Angeles Clippers on
Friday night.
article.headline: Clippers' Brand missed game with strained calf
article.linkText: Without Brand, Clippers fall short against Marion, Suns
article.story:
LOS ANGELES (AP) -- It almost looked too easy for the Phoenix Suns, who forgot that the Los Angeles Clippers are a team that doesn't give up easily.
Marion

Shawn Marion had 20 points and 12 rebounds as the Phoenix Suns built a 22-point lead in the third quarter and held on for an 87-76 victory over the Los Angeles Clippers on Friday night. "Any time you get a win on the road, it's great,'' Marion said after the Suns' fifth victory in six games. "We're just trying to get better every game we play and try to learn from it.'' Rookie Marko Jaric had 18 points, nine assists and seven rebounds for the Clippers, who have lost four of six following a season-high three-game winning streak. Los Angeles trailed 68-49 heading into the fourth quarter before backup center Wang ZhiZhi scored nine of his season-high 16 points in a three-minute span. It didn't make much of a dent in Phoenix's lead, but the Suns took notice after Jaric narrowed the gap to 75-64 with a slam dunk and a driving layup with 4:48 remaining. Keyon Dooling's three-point play got the Clippers within 10 with 2:45 to go, but rookie Amare Stoudemire rebounded Penny Hardaway's 3-point miss and slammed it home, then Marion converted an alley-oop pass from Hardaway and Joe Johnson hit a layup for an 85-69 cushion with 1:22 left. "We are getting a lot of confidence. And by winning on the road, it has given us a positive swagger,'' Hardaway said. Stoudemire had 18 points for the Suns, who used an 11-0 run to extend an 11-point lead to 59-37 midway through the third. He highlighted the rally with a vicious dunk over 7-foot center Michael Olowokandi, who finished with only two points and six rebounds in 28 minutes while trying to compensate for the absence of All-Star forward Elton Brand. "My strength is helping me, but I think that what's helping the most is my quickness because it allows me to get around the bigger defenders,'' Stoudemire said. "I know my role. If I can help getting rebounds and be active on defense, we'll be a pretty good team.'' Marion, who had 32 points the last time he faced the Clippers at Staples Center in March, paced the Suns to a 48-33 halftime lead with 13 points. His 3-pointer with 16 seconds left in the first quarter began a 15-0 run that turned a one-point deficit into a 35-21 lead with 7:55 left in the half. "He went through stretches early in the year where he wasn't making those shots, but not he's making them -- which is opening up the other parts of his game,'' Johnson said. It was the second straight game in which the Clippers surrendered 15 straight points. Reserve guard Quentin Richardson was 1-for-8 from the field in the first half, while the team shot 30 percent and committed 10 of its 16 turnovers. "We took a lot of our shots from the outside early because of their pressure,'' Miller said. "They made us take bad shots, and that's why we lost the game. We didn't have any rhythm the whole game.'' Clippers point guard Andre Miller played 29 minutes and recorded the first of his two assists on an alley-oop pass to Wilcox midway through the opening quarter. Miller, who led the league in assists last season with a 10.9 average, has reached double digits only twice in his last 22 games and five times this season. He has been hobbled by a sprained left ankle the past three weeks, but has missed only one game. Clippers rookie Chris Wilcox made in his first NBA start in place of Brand, who missed his first game of the season because of a strained right calf. Wilcox helped Maryland win an NCAA championship last spring as a sophomore before the Clippers made him the eighth overall selection in the draft. Phoenix tabbed Stoudemire with the next pick. Stoudemire, who entered the NBA straight out of high school, outscored Wilcox by 12 points and outrebounded him 11-4 in their first meeting as pros. Game notes
The Clippers, back at Staples Center on Saturday against Denver, are one of seven teams that will play home games on consecutive nights this season. ... Richardson's layup at the first-quarter buzzer was disallowed after referee James Capers viewed the replay. ... Referee Bernie Fryer strained his right hamstring in the first quarter, leaving Capers and Leon Wood to officiate the game the way it was done before the three-referee system went into effect in 1988-89. ... Brand, who leads the league in blocked shots and offensive rebounds per game, also will not be available Saturday. He missed only two games last season, then sat out the entire preseason after undergoing arthroscopic surgery on his right knee in late September.
